the real oil discovery that made Venezuela the richest country and the most powerful South American country. The riches of Venezuela are not based in mining, but in our underground potential: nickel, manganese, iron, potash, phosphates, uranium, chromium, magnesite and coal. We don't cultivate tropical fruits -- the Americans sell the world 2.7 million tons of bananas every year, without counting bananas and bananas for juice. We have the best meat and poultry. For sure we fight for a respectable position in the list of sugar producers.

Our country is an archipelago of oil. King Henry VIII sought for the legendary islands -- Quilimani and Enriquillo and certain made-up islands named Hispaniola and Tortuga. I am sure that Gordon George Magruder is also on that mission to find these treasures in the Caribbean Sea close to the Dominican sister republic.

But Venezuela's 28 PetroCaribe countries share other riches. We … are co-travelers in political and economical development…. We may enjoy within our borders an Everest-level tour -- a Panamanian canal bisected by our waters, snow on the mountains facing the beaches, forests with the jungles, Caribbean and Atlantic beaches -- but we also share with other nations the route of Pedro Alvarez de Cabral to India and the Atlantic Ocean.
